WEBVTT

00:08.009 --> 00:10.045
(SOFT INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC)

00:28.321 --> 00:30.562
(FAN FARE PLAYS)

00:34.327 --> 00:37.535
COMMENTATOR: More than half a million
people pack Epsom to bursting point.

00:37.622 --> 00:42.036
And now, to watch the Coronation Derby,
comes Her Majesty the Queen.

00:42.126 --> 00:44.082
Her oar, bearing the Royal Standard,

00:44.170 --> 00:47.378
moves slowly down the course
from Tattenham Corner.

00:47.465 --> 00:49.626
Accompanied by the Duke of Edinburgh,

00:49.717 --> 00:52.880
the Queen waves acknowledgment
to the welcoming cheers.

00:52.970 --> 00:56.679
The crowds pour their appreciation
for the dashing, handsome couple,

00:56.766 --> 01:00.054
a symbol of a new era.

01:01.979 --> 01:04.812
PETER: Half a million people.

01:07.276 --> 01:09.141
At a racecourse.

01:11.155 --> 01:16.821
Thanks to the coronation, your sister
is now the most famous woman in the world.

01:18.871 --> 01:19.951
Yes.

01:23.501 --> 01:25.162
But I'm the luckiest.

01:28.047 --> 01:32.381
-And on our romantic trip to Rhodesia...
-Officia| duty in Rhodesia.

01:32.718 --> 01:36.085
-(CHUCKLES) ...with the man I love...
-Secret|y love.

01:36.180 --> 01:39.138
...I will be the happiest.

01:40.017 --> 01:42.508
(COMMENTARY CONTIN U ES
|N BACKGROUND)

01:50.820 --> 01:52.310
(KEYS CLACKING)

01:52.405 --> 01:55.147
I've got a story, chief. It's important.

01:55.241 --> 01:57.903
As long as it's not about the Royal Family,
Bill, I'm all ears.

01:57.994 --> 02:00.110
It is about the Royal Family, chief.

02:00.204 --> 02:03.867
Ah, let me guess, how,
thanks to one beautiful young woman,

02:03.958 --> 02:06.745
one short televised ceremony...

02:06.836 --> 02:08.167
Oh, thank you, Bob.

02:08.254 --> 02:11.667
A tired anachronistic institution
is rejuvenated,

02:11.757 --> 02:15.966
a nation is liberated
from the austerity of rationing and war,

02:16.053 --> 02:18.965
our place as a leading power in the world
is re-established

02:19.056 --> 02:21.843
just when it seemed to be slipping.
What a load of bollocks.

02:21.934 --> 02:23.595
-MAN: Shifter?
-I shouldn't.

02:23.686 --> 02:26.803
-Oh, go on. It's nearly lunchtime.
-WOMAN: Papers, sir.

02:26.897 --> 02:28.307
-Thanks, Mary.
-MARY: My job.

02:28.399 --> 02:30.981
-lt's Princess Margaret.
-What about her?

02:31.068 --> 02:33.104
Leaving the Abbey
on the day of the coronation,

02:33.237 --> 02:36.729
I saw her picking a piece of fluff
off a man's uniform.

02:36.824 --> 02:38.780
-Fluff?
-Yes. Fluff.

02:38.868 --> 02:41.575
Jesus,BHL
I thought we did serious reporting here.

02:41.662 --> 02:46.122
This is serious. 'Cause the man in question,
her father's former equerry,

02:46.208 --> 02:49.666
Group Captain Peter Townsend,
is a commoner,

02:49.754 --> 02:53.121
and, wait for it, a divorced commoner.

02:54.133 --> 02:56.715
Historically,
when this lot brush up against divorce,

02:56.802 --> 02:59.760
you end up with either reformation,
or abdication.

02:59.847 --> 03:03.010
Will church and state clash again?
It's a big story.

03:03.100 --> 03:06.217
So are Cometjet planes
dropping out of the sky,

03:06.312 --> 03:10.351
Stalin's death ushering in a power reshuffle
in the Soviet Union.

03:10.441 --> 03:13.604
Let me write it up, chief.
I've got a feeling about this one.

03:13.778 --> 03:14.813
Based on what?

03:19.158 --> 03:20.773
What are you doing, man?

03:20.868 --> 03:25.908
Picking fluff off a man's jacket,
that's a gesture as intimate as a kiss,

03:25.998 --> 03:29.161
more intimate, since it suggests
the kiss has already happened.

03:31.170 --> 03:34.503
No. I'm sorry, Bill.
I can't hold the front page for a bit of fluff.

03:34.590 --> 03:37.297
Let me write it, chief. Then you decide.

03:39.428 --> 03:41.168
All right.

03:43.724 --> 03:46.386
Make sure it's peppery.

03:46.477 --> 03:48.263
-Make sure it pops.
-Yes, sir!

03:52.233 --> 03:54.269
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

05:06.974 --> 05:08.714
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

05:17.151 --> 05:19.483
Switchboard.
Good morning, Your Royal Highness.

05:19.737 --> 05:22.228
Good morning.
I would like to speak to my sister, please.

05:22.740 --> 05:24.776
One moment, please.

05:29.413 --> 05:32.746
-WOMAN: London.
-Buckingham Palace, please.

05:32.833 --> 05:36.826
-Victoria 48, 32.
-WOMAN: Hold the line.

05:36.921 --> 05:39.537
MAN: Buckingham Palace, good morning.

05:39.632 --> 05:41.247
WOMAN: Go ahead, please.

05:41.342 --> 05:44.880
MAN: I have Her Royal Highness
the Princess Margaret for Her Majesty.

05:44.970 --> 05:46.380
-Certainly, sir.
-Thank you.

05:46.472 --> 05:48.337
Can you hold the line?

05:48.432 --> 05:52.471
Sir, Princess Margaret for Her Majesty.

05:52.561 --> 05:53.937
Thank you.

06:02.905 --> 06:04.486
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

06:08.118 --> 06:09.949
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

06:17.127 --> 06:18.116
Hello?

06:18.337 --> 06:21.955
l have Her Royal Highness
the Princess Margaret, for Her Majesty.

06:22.132 --> 06:23.963
Yes, sir, breakfast room.

06:24.260 --> 06:26.672
-The breakfast room.
-MAN: Yes, sir.

06:27.972 --> 06:30.384
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)
-(KNOCK|NG)

06:31.475 --> 06:33.466
Telephone call for you, ma'am.

06:34.603 --> 06:36.343
-EL|ZABETH: Yes?
-(CLEARS THROAT)

06:36.564 --> 06:40.056
Her Royal Highness the Princess Margaret,
Your Majesty.

06:40.150 --> 06:41.185
Thank you.

06:42.861 --> 06:44.522
Hello, you.

06:44.697 --> 06:46.813
Hello, you.

06:47.032 --> 06:49.068
So, I was wondering
if you had a free evening soon

06:49.159 --> 06:50.615
where we all might have dinner together.

06:51.120 --> 06:53.862
-Before I go to Rhodesia.
-/’m sure I do.

06:53.956 --> 06:55.696
Thursday? Mummy's out.

06:55.833 --> 06:57.619
I'd have to check.

06:57.751 --> 07:00.458
-Lovely.
-And, who's "us all"?

07:02.214 --> 07:05.798
You, and me, and Philip and, um...

07:05.884 --> 07:08.375
And lwould like to bring Peter ifl may?

07:09.722 --> 07:11.007
What, "Peter" Peter?

07:11.515 --> 07:12.504
Yes, Peter.

07:13.851 --> 07:15.512
-Oh.
-What does that mean, "Oh"?

07:16.520 --> 07:19.227
Nothing. "Oh," how nice.

07:19.857 --> 07:22.314
There's something
we'd like to discuss with you.

07:22.568 --> 07:23.603
Oh?

07:23.694 --> 07:25.434
There you go again.

07:25.529 --> 07:29.238
Sorry. Am / going to be given a clue?

07:29.325 --> 07:30.314
No.

07:31.201 --> 07:32.190
Oh.

07:32.369 --> 07:35.202
-Stop it.
-Sorry.

07:35.331 --> 07:38.073
-So, Thursday evening, then? You’ll check?
-Fine.

07:43.172 --> 07:46.630
ltwill be such fun.

07:46.717 --> 07:47.957
Love/y.

07:51.847 --> 07:53.383
Lovely.

07:53.599 --> 07:54.714
(GIGGLES)

08:00.230 --> 08:01.640
(HANGS UP PHONE)

08:04.068 --> 08:05.308
Oh.

08:07.363 --> 08:09.900
Here we are.

08:09.990 --> 08:13.073
-Sir.
-Lovely, thank you.

08:19.249 --> 08:20.659
(LAUGHTER)

08:22.169 --> 08:24.000
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

08:31.595 --> 08:34.758
MAN 1: What's your name then, my darling?
MAN 2: Thank you, gentlemen, thank you.

08:34.848 --> 08:38.511
-Thank you very much, gentlemen.
-(ALL EXCLAIMING)

08:38.602 --> 08:40.467
You're too kind, you're too kind.

08:40.646 --> 08:42.932
A special guestjoins us this afternoon,

08:43.440 --> 08:47.103
who's just returned from a year
in post-revolutionary Cairo

08:47.194 --> 08:48.855
working as a photojournalist.

08:48.946 --> 08:51.779
Our fellow lunch club member,
Tony Longdon.

08:51.865 --> 08:53.480
-All night, Longdonl
-(ALL CHEERING)

08:56.120 --> 08:58.736
Thank you, chaps,
it's very nice to be back, I must say.

08:59.123 --> 09:01.865
Ladies, might we close the shutters, please?

09:01.959 --> 09:04.541
(ALL EXCLAIM)

09:04.628 --> 09:06.619
(LAUGHTER)

09:06.714 --> 09:08.250
MAN: Lovely!

09:08.340 --> 09:12.458
I am, as Baron says,
fresh from the streets of Cairo,

09:12.970 --> 09:16.963
and I'm still trying to digest
the hurricane of popular uprising,

09:17.141 --> 09:21.225
violent military coup,
and revolution that l have just witnessed.

09:21.478 --> 09:22.979
MAN: Bloody natives.

09:23.063 --> 09:26.396
You all know King Farouk.
Colorful character.

09:26.483 --> 09:30.852
-He owned more than 100 cars.
-MAN: Almost as much as me.

09:30.946 --> 09:33.688
-Had them all painted red.
-MAN: Splendid.

09:33.782 --> 09:36.068
He used to race them
through streets of Cairo,

09:36.160 --> 09:38.742
shooting at any pedestrians
who happened to get in his way.

09:38.829 --> 09:41.411
-Hear, hear!
-Peasant shoot!

09:41.498 --> 09:42.999
(LAUGHTER)

09:43.167 --> 09:46.159
Probably why he was forced
to abdicate last year.

09:47.171 --> 09:53.041
And now, this man, Nasser,
is the name on everyone's lips.

09:53.135 --> 09:55.842
He has the charisma to unite
notjust his own country,

09:55.929 --> 09:57.840
but the entire Arab world.

09:58.682 --> 10:03.016
Stirring up anti-Western,
anti-monarchical sentiment.

10:06.774 --> 10:09.436
This is Shepheard's.

10:11.111 --> 10:14.774
A famous British hotel.
A symbol of colonial rule.

10:16.074 --> 10:17.234
Before riots...

10:19.703 --> 10:22.911
-MAN: God.
-...and after.

10:23.123 --> 10:26.536
That writing. What does it say?

10:29.379 --> 10:32.121
"Death to the imperialists."

10:35.135 --> 10:37.626
However, it's not all doom and gloom.

10:37.721 --> 10:40.337
Mike, got something
a little special for you here.

10:40.432 --> 10:41.638
(ALL CHEERING)

10:41.725 --> 10:43.181
MIKE: Now, that's exactly
what I'm talking about.

10:50.776 --> 10:53.313
-(TIRES SCREECHING)
-Whool

11:04.081 --> 11:05.366
(LAUGHING)

11:06.416 --> 11:09.749
-Give him a tip.
-Don't tell my wife.

11:09.920 --> 11:11.501
(BOTH LAUGH)

11:11.588 --> 11:12.668
Good tip.

11:18.011 --> 11:20.297
-Where were you today?
-Nowhere.

11:20.389 --> 11:23.552
Well, clearly somewhere,
but nowhere that would interest you.

11:23.642 --> 11:25.803
It's a lunch club.

11:25.894 --> 11:28.556
-Where?
-Soho.

11:30.482 --> 11:31.767
Oh.

11:33.527 --> 11:36.360
With just men.

11:36.446 --> 11:38.823
Talking about women.

11:38.907 --> 11:42.240
No. Talking about Egypt, if you must know,

11:42.327 --> 11:44.659
and the revolution
that's just taken place there.

11:44.955 --> 11:50.621
Along with the unrest in Croatia, Albania,
Montenegro, Yugoslavia, Hungary, Italy.

11:51.003 --> 11:52.664
Please take note.

11:55.340 --> 11:58.628
Yes, a little bit about the fairer sex
over coffee and the odd brandy.

12:00.137 --> 12:03.629
What do you expect?
It's a gentlemen's lunch club.

12:11.982 --> 12:14.598
-So, what's the guest list for tonight?
-Mmm. No one.

12:14.693 --> 12:17.685
Just you, me, Margaret, and Peter.

12:17.779 --> 12:21.692
What? "Townsend" Peter?

12:21.783 --> 12:24.866
-Then why on Earth did we have to dress up?
-She insisted.

12:24.953 --> 12:27.114
She wanted to make it a special occasion.

12:27.205 --> 12:29.867
With him? Isn't that a contradiction in terms?

12:31.668 --> 12:34.159
He's not been a naughty boy, has he?

12:35.756 --> 12:38.418
I know as much as you do.

12:52.356 --> 12:54.017
It will be fine.

13:04.159 --> 13:05.365
Come on.

13:10.123 --> 13:13.581
-We'd like to be left alone now.
-Yes, ma'am.

13:16.505 --> 13:18.245
Just leave it.

13:19.299 --> 13:20.584
Thank you.

13:37.234 --> 13:38.349
Excuse me.

13:44.574 --> 13:47.156
I asked you here tonight because

13:47.244 --> 13:49.951
there is something
I wanted to discuss with you.

13:50.872 --> 13:52.828
I think you already know that over the years,

13:52.916 --> 13:58.001
with Peter being so much part of our family,
and away from his own so much,

13:58.088 --> 14:00.704
a friendship has developed between us.

14:03.927 --> 14:07.419
And then, ever since
Papa's death hitting me so hard,

14:07.514 --> 14:13.259
and with your accession and coronation
and you being more and more occupied,

14:14.187 --> 14:19.227
Peter has become almost
my sole companion, and I his.

14:20.944 --> 14:24.983
And so, when his divorce came through
in December last year,

14:25.073 --> 14:29.442
I suppose it was only natural that we both
started thinking about what kind of

14:31.580 --> 14:35.368
future we might have together,

14:35.876 --> 14:38.288
and we reached a decision in April, wasn't it?

14:38.378 --> 14:40.960
Just before the coronation...

14:42.591 --> 14:44.422
That, one day,

14:47.387 --> 14:48.672
we wanted to...

14:55.395 --> 14:56.851
Well, you know...

14:57.439 --> 14:59.851
-Marry?
-(LAUGHS) Yes.

15:01.234 --> 15:02.690
ELIZABETH: Goodness.

15:05.238 --> 15:09.106
Well, of course, we're aware
of the complications and issues at stake.

15:17.292 --> 15:19.704
Well, Lilibet, you've known for a while
about Peter and I.

15:21.630 --> 15:25.623
This can't really be a terrible shock to you.

15:25.842 --> 15:27.503
No, not at all.

15:29.596 --> 15:30.836
It's wonderful.

15:31.807 --> 15:35.174
-Is there anything you'd like to ask us?
-Does your wife know?

15:35.268 --> 15:39.011
-No, ex-wife.
-She does. We had a frank conversation.

15:39.106 --> 15:41.643
-There is no animosity.
-Good.

15:41.733 --> 15:45.476
-And the boys?
-They know, and seem very happy.

15:50.408 --> 15:51.818
So,

15:53.036 --> 15:55.072
do I have your permission?

15:57.457 --> 15:59.994
As Sovereign?

16:03.547 --> 16:04.536
Oh.

16:09.010 --> 16:10.090
Well...

16:11.721 --> 16:14.133
Of course, I'll have to take advice

16:15.559 --> 16:20.553
on the hows and wheres,
and all official matters,

16:20.939 --> 16:24.272
but if it's what you desire...

16:27.112 --> 16:29.694
More than anything in the world.

16:31.741 --> 16:33.732
Well, then as your sister,
I'm never going to oppose it.

16:34.327 --> 16:36.989
(GASPS) Thank you. Thank you.

16:39.082 --> 16:42.495
Thank you. I'm so happy. I'm so happy.
Thank you.

16:42.586 --> 16:46.829
Well, congratulations to the both of you.

16:46.923 --> 16:48.174
(LAUGHS)

16:48.592 --> 16:49.877
Thank you, sir.

16:49.968 --> 16:51.754
I suppose it had better be "Philip"
from now on.

16:51.887 --> 16:52.876
Thank you, sir. Philip.

17:01.438 --> 17:02.598
PHILIP: You knew?

17:05.233 --> 17:06.894
Not the extent of it.

17:09.279 --> 17:11.144
But you didn't think to mention it?

17:15.660 --> 17:16.911
/ don 't like it.

17:17.037 --> 17:20.621
Any of it. For one thing,
it will create the most enormous scandal.

17:20.707 --> 17:23.995
Nor do I believe in them as a couple.
He's too old for her.

17:24.085 --> 17:27.122
And he had some sort of breakdown
during the war.

17:27.255 --> 17:29.041
ELIZABETH: NOW, that's all in the past.

17:29.132 --> 17:32.215
Besides, that's why
he got on with my father so well.

17:32.302 --> 17:35.715
-Not to mention the fact he's dull.
-He's not dull.

17:35.805 --> 17:40.014
Desperately dull. I'm confident
I've met more interesting plants.

17:40.101 --> 17:43.184
Not to mention,
it's a terrible thing to do to you.

17:43.313 --> 17:44.644
VVhy?

17:44.731 --> 17:49.725
Because of the position it puts you in
as a sister and as a Queen.

17:49.819 --> 17:53.778
Has everyone forgotten
the catastrophe that was your uncle already?

17:53.865 --> 17:59.735
-The situation's different.
-One party divorced, the other royal.

17:59.913 --> 18:01.744
Sounds pretty similar to me.

18:01.831 --> 18:05.415
That was 17 years ago.
The world has changed.

18:05.502 --> 18:10.747
The rest of the world has.
Nothing changes in the Court of St. James's.

18:10.840 --> 18:14.082
Besides, we have a son and heir.

18:14.177 --> 18:17.260
There's no realistic prospect
of Margaret becoming Queen.

18:18.014 --> 18:21.848
And one can see the attraction.

18:24.437 --> 18:25.472
In Peter?

18:26.481 --> 18:30.599
Yes. He's a handsome war hero.

18:30.694 --> 18:34.858
-Divorced war hero.
-And blameless in that divorce.

18:34.948 --> 18:39.282
No. There's no such thing
as a blameless party in a divorce.

18:39.369 --> 18:42.281
His wife had an affair with another man.

18:42.372 --> 18:44.829
Because he was always around here,
sniffing around your sister.

18:45.959 --> 18:49.543
-He was looking after my father.
-And sniffing around your sister. (LAUGHS)

18:50.630 --> 18:52.461
Stop it.

18:52.549 --> 18:55.131
Anyway, I thought you liked him.

18:56.052 --> 19:00.967
Oh... Liked him? I mean, I respect him
for what he did in the war, certainly.

19:01.057 --> 19:03.799
He plays bridge well. And he's a good pilot.

19:05.228 --> 19:08.015
-And he's a good influence on Margaret.
-Is he?

19:08.106 --> 19:10.848
If he were really a good influence,
he'd patch things up with his wife,

19:10.942 --> 19:13.183
and leave Margaret well alone.

19:25.999 --> 19:28.206
(TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING)

19:31.171 --> 19:33.913
-Night, Bill.
-Good night.

19:37.177 --> 19:38.542
BILL: "...potentially..."

19:57.280 --> 19:59.271
-Good night, sir.
-Yeah.

19:59.366 --> 20:02.278
This had better be good.

20:02.369 --> 20:03.575
It is.

20:06.623 --> 20:10.115
-(SIGHS) Bloody hell.
-You did say "peppery."

20:10.210 --> 20:14.328
-Pepper is one thing. This is gelignite.
-I know.

20:22.347 --> 20:25.134
-What are you doing?
-I can't run this without going upstairs.

20:25.225 --> 20:27.307
-What?
-Don't look at me like that.

20:27.435 --> 20:30.472
Live in the real bloody world
for a moment, will you?

20:32.232 --> 20:35.599
Margery, hello, yes. Is he there?

20:35.693 --> 20:37.900
Yeah, just for a few minutes.

20:40.657 --> 20:44.491
This is notjust inflammatory,
it breaks all the rules.

20:44.577 --> 20:45.566
What rules, sir?

20:45.662 --> 20:49.154
The unspoken rules of deference and respect

20:49.249 --> 20:51.240
shown by the media to the Royal Family.

20:51.334 --> 20:52.870
But surely, those rules changed

20:52.961 --> 20:55.327
the moment
they invited television into the coronation.

20:55.755 --> 20:58.462
That was their right, and a huge concession.

20:58.550 --> 21:00.757
-To what?
-Popular interest.

21:00.844 --> 21:02.550
Their interest also.

21:02.720 --> 21:05.382
Look at their standing now,
it's never been higher.

21:05.473 --> 21:09.466
The question we in the fourth estate
need to be asking ourselves is,

21:09.561 --> 21:13.429
"Do we let ourselves be used,
or do we have our own independent voice?"

21:13.523 --> 21:15.388
Don't get moralistic with me.

21:15.525 --> 21:18.938
If we don't break this story,
do you think nobody else will?

21:19.028 --> 21:22.816
I know there's plenty of others
sniffing around it, sir.

21:29.539 --> 21:31.029
Thank you for letting me know.

21:31.124 --> 21:34.366
Of course, Tommy,
thank you for understanding.

21:35.044 --> 21:37.786
-I'm sorry.
-No, I'm sorry.

21:37.922 --> 21:42.211
I imagine it must be difficult
being dictated to like that by an employee.

21:42.427 --> 21:45.339
-I wasn't dictated to.
-Am I missing something?

21:45.430 --> 21:46.966
You said this editor was telling you

21:47.056 --> 21:49.138
what he was going to print
in your newspaper.

21:49.225 --> 21:53.343
He is.
But I can't keep telling him what to write.

21:53.438 --> 21:56.305
I thought that was the point
of owning a newspaper.

21:56.399 --> 21:58.640
Look, I'm just trying to help you, Tommy.

21:58.735 --> 22:01.818
I suggest you see this
for the kind gesture that it is.

22:01.905 --> 22:04.692
What, that you are about to print an article

22:04.782 --> 22:08.366
that will cause deep distress to senior,
let's be quite clear,

22:08.453 --> 22:10.660
the most senior members
of the Royal Family?

22:10.747 --> 22:14.410
That I'm warning you.
That I'm giving you the heads up.

22:15.418 --> 22:18.706
I'm on my knees with gratitude.

22:29.891 --> 22:32.758
(INFERNAL GALOP FROM ORPHEUS
IN THE UNDERWORLD PLAYS)

22:40.944 --> 22:43.560
(CHATTER AND LAUGHTER)

22:52.580 --> 22:53.786
(BOTH GIGGLE)

23:04.467 --> 23:05.968
(LAUGHTER CONTIN U ES)

23:07.178 --> 23:09.009
Stop.

23:13.685 --> 23:15.801
Can you shut that?

23:27.365 --> 23:29.321
-(MUSIC CONTINUES)
-(LAUGHTER)

23:39.002 --> 23:39.991
Your Majesty.

23:40.086 --> 23:44.125
A story is about to break in the press

23:44.215 --> 23:50.051
identifying Peter Townsend notjust
as the companion of Princess Margaret,

23:52.557 --> 23:57.267
but as her likely future husband.

23:57.645 --> 24:02.139
We understand
that the paper is to feature a profile

24:02.233 --> 24:04.098
of Group Captain Townsend,

24:04.193 --> 24:09.062
details of his marriage
and subsequent divorce,

24:09.157 --> 24:13.742
along with an editorial
about other notable divorcees

24:13.828 --> 24:17.366
to have been associated
with members of the Royal Family.

24:26.382 --> 24:28.373
Should we deny it all?

24:31.512 --> 24:34.675
With respect, ma'am, it's a little late for that.

24:34.766 --> 24:37.974
This horse has already bolted.

24:44.233 --> 24:45.564
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

24:46.027 --> 24:47.892
Your Royal Highness?

24:49.530 --> 24:51.236
(SIGHS)

24:59.832 --> 25:00.821
Mmm?

25:00.917 --> 25:05.251
Her Majesty the Queen for you,
Your Royal Highness. On the telephone.

25:11.260 --> 25:12.340
Hello.

25:12.428 --> 25:14.635
Hello, you. Bad time, good time?

25:15.556 --> 25:18.514
(CHUCKLES) Good time. Always.

25:18.601 --> 25:22.344
Look, I've been wracking my brain
about how I can best help you.

25:22.438 --> 25:24.178
Now, you know that the Church of England

25:24.273 --> 25:26.730
doesn't permit the remarriage
of divorced persons

25:26.818 --> 25:29.400
if the husband or wife
of a former marriage is still alive.

25:29.487 --> 25:30.647
Yes.

25:30.738 --> 25:34.481
Well, I was just wondering
if you and Peter had considered Scotland.

25:34.575 --> 25:37.408
-To live?
-No, for the wedding.

25:37.620 --> 25:40.612
Why? Because it would be more low profile?

25:40.998 --> 25:44.365
Well, actually,
I was thinking of legal reasons.

25:44.502 --> 25:47.335
Marriage isn't regarded as a sacrament
in the Church of Scotland.

25:47.422 --> 25:50.038
It is not as binding in the same way as here.

25:52.009 --> 25:55.422
Meaning... Meaning we could
even get married in a church?

25:55.513 --> 25:59.347
Well, I’d have to check, but I think so.

25:59.434 --> 26:02.221
That would be so lovely.

26:02.311 --> 26:04.688
Lilibet, thank you so much.

26:05.773 --> 26:07.684
It would make my life a lot easier, too.

26:12.572 --> 26:13.687
Sorry, Lilibet.

26:14.073 --> 26:16.450
What for?

26:16.534 --> 26:20.152
/ think you’re going to get a visit
from Mummy about all this.

26:21.581 --> 26:24.914
I realize I'm not making anyone's life easy.

26:25.001 --> 26:26.491
Yours especially.

26:28.588 --> 26:30.954
But I'm determined to do this for you.

26:34.177 --> 26:35.587
Thank you.

26:37.054 --> 26:40.717
-I can’t wait to tell Peter.
-I'd better go.

26:55.406 --> 26:57.021
-Tommy.
-Your Majesty.

27:18.721 --> 27:22.805
Mummy. This is a surprise.

27:25.228 --> 27:29.597
I am a mother of two daughters
whom I love equally.

27:29.690 --> 27:33.683
It seems that they each have problems
of equal size.

27:35.822 --> 27:39.781
Obviously, we want Margaret to be happy,
to have the man she wants.

27:39.867 --> 27:41.107
Yes.

27:43.037 --> 27:47.827
But we must do everything in our power
to protect you as Queen.

27:47.917 --> 27:51.330
-And as a sister.
-Protect me from what?

27:51.420 --> 27:55.663
I've given Margaret my word,
and I'm determined to support her.

27:55.758 --> 27:59.046
They can marry in Scotland,
where I'm not head of the church.

27:59.136 --> 28:03.630
Your Majesty,
I fear the matter is more intricate.

28:03.933 --> 28:04.968
Let's be quite clear.

28:05.059 --> 28:08.392
If Margaret were to marry Peter,
it would be a scandal.

28:10.022 --> 28:15.267
Don't mistake your current popularity
for long-term security.

28:16.070 --> 28:20.313
Your uncle's affair and abdication
almost destroyed the Monarchy.

28:20.616 --> 28:23.323
This could, too.

28:24.954 --> 28:25.989
Tommy?

28:33.212 --> 28:37.455
Ma'am, what do you know
about the Royal Marriages Act of 1772?

28:38.634 --> 28:40.886
-George II?
-III, ma'am.

28:40.970 --> 28:44.258
He had two younger brothers,
William and Henry.

28:44.348 --> 28:47.010
Both of whom, I'm assuming,
made undesirable marriages.

28:47.101 --> 28:51.845
One to an illegitimate shrew,
the other to a disreputable jade,

28:51.939 --> 28:54.897
which caused an outrage
in parliament and the church.

28:54.984 --> 28:59.398
Now, in response, George III
asked his Prime Minister, Lord North,

28:59.488 --> 29:01.820
to rush through a Royal Marriages Act

29:01.908 --> 29:05.116
to prevent any future willful young prince

29:05.202 --> 29:09.741
or princess from making an ill-advised
or disadvantageous match,

29:10.041 --> 29:12.908
which might threaten
the integrity of the Royal house.

29:13.169 --> 29:17.754
It decrees that until the age of 25,
any member of the Royal Family

29:17.840 --> 29:22.083
must secure
the Sovereign's permission to marry.

29:25.264 --> 29:28.131
-But?
-But not thereafter.

29:30.853 --> 29:32.593
I see.

29:33.522 --> 29:37.185
So, if Margaret were to wait
until after her 25th birthday,

29:37.276 --> 29:41.394
she would be free to make any decision
she likes without your consent.

29:42.031 --> 29:43.567
The important thing is,

29:43.699 --> 29:48.489
it protects your relationship
with both church and government.

29:50.498 --> 29:56.118
Well, I can see the advantages of that.
But what's in it for her?

29:56.212 --> 29:59.955
Mummy, she's only 23.
What does she do in the meantime?

30:01.717 --> 30:04.880
In the meantime, she and Peter wait.

30:06.514 --> 30:08.505
Preferably, in separate countries.

30:08.975 --> 30:10.590
What?

30:10.685 --> 30:13.802
It's the only way to contain the story, ma'am.

30:21.112 --> 30:22.898
(EXHALES)

30:28.077 --> 30:29.408
MAN: Thank you, sir.

30:35.751 --> 30:38.128
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

30:40.339 --> 30:42.079
(BRAKES SCREECH)

30:45.970 --> 30:48.211
-MAN: Good morning, sir.
-Out of my way!

30:58.149 --> 31:00.060
-(KNOCKING ON DOOR)
-TOMMY: Come.

31:19.462 --> 31:21.248
ELIZABETH: Margaret!
MARGARET: No!

31:25.801 --> 31:27.587
Margaret!

31:30.389 --> 31:34.849
Just until your 25th birthday.
Then you would be free to do as you wish.

31:34.935 --> 31:39.224
Look me in the eye and tell me.
Is it a posting, or is it a banishment?

31:39.315 --> 31:43.228
It's a posting. I promise.

31:44.528 --> 31:48.316
It's just a way of managing the story,
keeping it off the front pages.

31:48.407 --> 31:52.525
-Not a heartless attempt to split us up?
-No, of course not.

31:52.620 --> 31:54.736
Papa did the same for Philip and me.
He made us wait.

31:54.830 --> 31:59.540
For three months. This is for two years.
Think of it. Two years.

32:07.802 --> 32:10.384
Why did you even dangle Scotland
under my nose?

32:15.017 --> 32:16.223
Sorry.

32:40.960 --> 32:42.450
All right.

32:45.589 --> 32:49.958
If I do this for you, will you promise me
that this banishment...

32:50.052 --> 32:51.041
Posting.

32:51.137 --> 32:53.344
This banishment won't start
until after our trip to Rhodesia?

32:53.430 --> 32:56.467
You know how much
we've been looking forward to it.

33:01.230 --> 33:04.142
You're going to deny us that as well?

33:04.233 --> 33:07.100
It's the sensitivity of you two together.

33:07.194 --> 33:10.903
The photographers.
It would overshadow everything.

33:10.990 --> 33:16.155
But when you get back,
you'll have some time together.

33:16.245 --> 33:18.782
Alone.

33:18.873 --> 33:21.239
I promise you that.

34:00.289 --> 34:03.873
PETER: They offered me Johannesburg.
I refused.

34:03.959 --> 34:05.165
Then Singapore.

34:07.463 --> 34:09.249
I refused that, too.

34:11.300 --> 34:13.416
Then they came back with Brussels.

34:15.471 --> 34:17.462
It's dreary, but at least it's close.

34:17.556 --> 34:21.048
The whole thing feels like
a completely unnecessary,

34:21.143 --> 34:25.728
-unjustifiable punishment.
-I know.

34:25.814 --> 34:29.272
Perhaps your sister sensed that.

34:29.360 --> 34:31.601
That is why
she's asked me to go to Northern Ireland.

34:32.696 --> 34:33.902
What for?

34:33.989 --> 34:37.573
To accompany her
on her trip to Belfast this week.

34:37.660 --> 34:40.743
To put on a show of public approval.

34:40.829 --> 34:42.740
That's something, I suppose.

34:42.831 --> 34:43.991
Hmm.

34:45.251 --> 34:47.663
No substitute for Rhodesia, though.

34:53.676 --> 34:56.008
No one wanted Philip.

34:58.472 --> 35:02.806
She dug her heels in,
got the man she wanted, didn't she?

35:04.561 --> 35:05.812
She did.

35:10.901 --> 35:13.062
We ought to head back.

35:14.863 --> 35:18.071
-Come on.
-No, wait. Kiss me.

35:28.836 --> 35:31.999
You know we won't be able to
back at the house.

35:55.571 --> 35:57.778
(ENGINE ROARS)

36:03.829 --> 36:07.071
-Your Majesty.
-Tommy.

36:07.166 --> 36:09.248
Just to run through the order of the day.

36:09.335 --> 36:12.327
-Yes.
-We'll be met at the airport

36:12.421 --> 36:14.833
by the Governor of Northern Ireland,
Lord Wakehurst.

36:15.049 --> 36:18.667
From there, we will be going
to the Belfast City boundary

36:18.761 --> 36:21.594
to be met by
the Lieutenant of the City of Belfast.

36:21.680 --> 36:26.720
After that, we will be presented to
the Lord Mayor, Alderman Percival Brown,

36:26.810 --> 36:29.973
and the Town Clerk, Mr. John Dunlop,

36:30.064 --> 36:33.101
followed by a city luncheon at Civic Hall.

36:33.776 --> 36:37.610
-The other way around, I think.
-Ma'am?

36:38.864 --> 36:41.446
A civic luncheon at City Hall.

36:44.995 --> 36:46.326
Hmm.

36:46.413 --> 36:48.904
-Forgive me.
-|s everything all right?

36:52.378 --> 36:57.498
I do hope it wasn't a mistake
inviting the Group Captain to join us.

36:59.802 --> 37:01.417
You've never cared for him, Tommy.

37:01.512 --> 37:05.346
No, I cared for him as long as he did his job,
and knew his place.

37:06.809 --> 37:08.720
My father held him in high regard.

37:08.811 --> 37:12.224
As a member of staff,
not as a member of the family.

37:14.525 --> 37:16.766
He has been a good friend to us all.

37:16.860 --> 37:20.478
Too good, I would argue.
And he let his wife go in the process.

37:22.074 --> 37:23.905
He was innocent in that regard.

37:25.035 --> 37:29.449
She left of her own accord.
And he's a wonderful father to those boys.

37:29.540 --> 37:32.828
I'm just trying to manage
a difficult situation, ma'am.

37:33.043 --> 37:34.874
As am I.

37:35.170 --> 37:38.378
Sending him away
will break my sister's heart.

37:38.674 --> 37:41.586
Hearts mend.

37:43.846 --> 37:46.633
Was there anything else?

37:46.974 --> 37:49.511
-No.
-Your Majesty.

38:07.202 --> 38:09.363
(CROWD CHEERING)

38:25.637 --> 38:28.925
(INDISTINCT CHATTER AND COMMENTARY)

38:29.266 --> 38:32.554
COMMENTATOR: ...bringing Her Majesty
the Queen on a visit to Northern Ireland.

38:36.148 --> 38:39.356
Her Majesty now walks
towards 3-year-old Eileen Hall,

38:39.443 --> 38:41.980
who presents her with a bouquet.

38:42.946 --> 38:46.109
The Queen, who wears a coat of
vivid blue shantung with a matching hat,

38:46.241 --> 38:49.153
ﬁnds herself sharing the limelight
with Group Captain Townsend,

38:49.244 --> 38:51.200
who accompanies her on the tour.

38:52.789 --> 38:54.916
The crowd get a last glimpse
of the Queen and her husband

38:55.167 --> 38:57.203
before they begin the drive to City Hall.

38:57.419 --> 39:01.128
En route, thousands pack the streets
to bid them welcome.

39:01.215 --> 39:02.921
(CROWD CHEERING)

39:05.511 --> 39:08.298
The royal couple are welcomed
onto Balmoral Showground,

39:08.388 --> 39:11.551
where 4,000 ex-servicemen and women
are gathered

39:11.642 --> 39:13.257
to pay tribute to their Sovereign.

39:13.352 --> 39:16.640
Many Ulster schools
and youth organizations are represented,

39:16.730 --> 39:19.847
and they all have a smile
and a wave for the Queen.

39:22.194 --> 39:25.937
As London papers called once more today
for a statement from Buckingham Palace

39:26.031 --> 39:28.818
to clarify the rumors of a romance
between Princess Margaret

39:28.909 --> 39:30.524
and Group Captain Townsend,

39:30.619 --> 39:33.611
newspaper editors from all over the world
sent their photographers

39:33.705 --> 39:37.323
to scrutinize Townsend’s face,
hoping for a clue.

39:37.626 --> 39:39.332
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

39:44.383 --> 39:47.796
The Queen can’t be used to sharing the
limelight with a member of her household.

39:47.886 --> 39:50.093
But the gathered crowds
certainly seem as interested

39:50.180 --> 39:53.172
in Group Captain Townsend
as in Her Majesty.

39:57.771 --> 39:59.887
-Turn it off.
-Certainly, ma'am.

39:59.982 --> 40:03.065
The crowds had to jostle with members
of the press and television

40:03.151 --> 40:05.016
for following the royal party’s every move.

40:09.157 --> 40:12.445
I brought him along to show my gratitude
for his years of service

40:12.536 --> 40:14.572
and to support my sister.

40:14.663 --> 40:18.781
And I had hoped that attention
on Margaret and Peter would fade away.

40:19.960 --> 40:22.167
But I could barely hear myself speak today.

40:22.254 --> 40:26.247
-The solution is an obvious one.
-Which is?

40:26.341 --> 40:30.960
Bring forward the Group Captain's relocation
with immediate effect.

40:31.054 --> 40:35.593
But that would mean him missing
his reunion with my sister in London.

40:35.684 --> 40:37.049
And I gave her my word.

40:37.144 --> 40:41.934
Well, sometimes best intentions
need to be reconsidered, Your Majesty.

40:42.024 --> 40:44.561
You can always blame it on me.

40:46.778 --> 40:52.148
No. Let's wait 24 hours.
Things might calm down tomorrow.

40:52.242 --> 40:53.948
-WOMAN: Your Majesty.
-Your Majesty.

40:54.036 --> 40:57.949
The Lambeg drummers, ma'am.
A special Orangemen's welcome.

40:58.206 --> 41:00.333
-Your Majesty.
-Your Majesty.

41:02.461 --> 41:05.248
-(DRUMM|NG)
-(CROWD CHEERING)

41:08.884 --> 41:11.250
-(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)
-(DRUMM|NG CONTINUES)

41:18.268 --> 41:20.224
REPORTER 1: Townsend?
REPORTER 2: Captain Townsend?

41:22.230 --> 41:25.097
MAN 1: Townsend.
MAN 2: Captain.

41:30.155 --> 41:31.736
(ALL CHEERING)

41:36.620 --> 41:38.781
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

41:47.214 --> 41:48.795
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

41:49.091 --> 41:52.754
May God give you wisdom, loyalty

41:53.970 --> 41:55.301
and faithfulness.

41:56.431 --> 42:01.016
And may the future bring peace,
contentment and true happiness

42:01.520 --> 42:04.136
to the people of Northern Ireland.

42:04.231 --> 42:05.596
(APPLAUSE)

42:06.525 --> 42:08.481
(ALL CHEERING)

42:14.574 --> 42:16.610
MAN 1: Townsend!
MAN 2: Townsend!

42:23.041 --> 42:24.326
Townsend!

42:56.324 --> 42:58.064
Do you have a moment, Lilibet?

43:02.205 --> 43:03.991
Yes, of course.

43:08.795 --> 43:12.913
I just wanted to apologize
for all the press attention.

43:13.341 --> 43:16.925
And to thank you for inviting me along
in the first place.

43:17.012 --> 43:19.424
I do appreciate the gesture.

43:20.432 --> 43:22.297
It's the least I could do.

43:22.392 --> 43:24.929
I regretted having to take you off
the Rhodesia trip.

43:25.020 --> 43:27.056
Yes.
Margaret and I were so looking forward to it.

43:27.147 --> 43:29.138
We have so many shared interests,
as you know,

43:29.232 --> 43:33.145
we enjoy doing everything together.

43:35.947 --> 43:40.816
We had hoped to find some time together
during her days off.

43:40.911 --> 43:43.869
Walking, swimming, riding.

43:46.041 --> 43:49.033
But not to be.

43:52.172 --> 43:53.161
No.

43:59.262 --> 44:01.218
Anyway, nice Chatting.

44:07.938 --> 44:09.644
Ma'am, if you wouldn't mind.

44:15.529 --> 44:19.943
Just wondering if Her Majesty
has had time to think about the matter.

44:22.118 --> 44:23.244
She has.

44:26.081 --> 44:30.120
Take care of it, Tommy.
In whatever manner you see fit.

44:32.337 --> 44:33.452
Yes, ma'am.

44:47.602 --> 44:51.345
-(CROWD CHEERING)
-(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

45:04.619 --> 45:08.111
MAN 1: Thank you, Your Majesty.
MAN 2: Good night, sir.

45:08.206 --> 45:10.117
Thank you so much, Peter.

45:12.752 --> 45:14.913
Ma'am.

45:19.467 --> 45:22.083
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

45:51.374 --> 45:53.239
TOMMY: Group Captain Townsend.

45:57.088 --> 45:59.079
The "Man of the Moment."

46:01.718 --> 46:03.379
Do come up.

46:12.520 --> 46:14.181
Will you sit?

46:24.866 --> 46:28.233
Following consultation
with the government, the Foreign Office,

46:28.328 --> 46:30.410
and Her Majesty's press secretary,

46:30.497 --> 46:33.489
the decision has been taken
to move forward your posting

46:33.583 --> 46:35.539
to Brussels with immediate effect.

46:35.627 --> 46:38.118
A car is waiting
to take you first to your apartment,

46:38.213 --> 46:41.455
where you will pack,
and then directly to the airfield.

46:41.549 --> 46:45.167
The plane for Brussels
leaves in just under three hours.

46:45.261 --> 46:48.298
There was some concern
that that might not give you enough time,

46:48.390 --> 46:52.053
but I felt sure that as a military man,
packing quickly

46:52.227 --> 46:55.936
and unsentimentally
would come as second nature to you.

46:58.900 --> 47:00.265
But that isn't what was agreed.

47:03.488 --> 47:06.821
The agreement between
Margaret and Her Majesty the Queen,

47:06.908 --> 47:09.024
with the certain knowledge
of Her Majesty the Queen Mother,

47:09.119 --> 47:11.952
was that Margaret and I
were to spend some time together

47:12.038 --> 47:14.245
upon her return from Rhodesia,

47:14.332 --> 47:17.745
before I traveled to Brussels.
Forty-eight hours at least.

47:18.962 --> 47:22.204
Your proposal is a direct contravention
of that agreement.

47:23.299 --> 47:28.965
Well, I cannot, nor would I ever presume
to know the intimate details

47:29.055 --> 47:32.889
of whatever agreements have
or have not been made within the family.

47:33.435 --> 47:37.769
What I can tell you is that the position
of air attache at the embassy fell vacant

47:37.856 --> 47:41.565
unexpectedly early
and needs filling right away.

47:41.651 --> 47:44.188
Of course, a crucial position

47:44.279 --> 47:47.942
like the air attache
to the embassy at Brussels

47:48.033 --> 47:49.989
cannot be left vacant for very long.

47:50.076 --> 47:55.161
I ask only that it remain so
until after the Princess returns,

47:55.248 --> 47:58.581
as I was promised.

48:00.795 --> 48:03.628
I'm afraid that will not be possible.

48:15.602 --> 48:17.138
Tommy,

48:19.647 --> 48:22.309
I understand
you're only trying to do yourjob.

48:23.860 --> 48:27.899
But one thing the trip to Northern Ireland
has made very Clear to me

48:28.073 --> 48:33.067
is that the romance between Margaret
and myself has caught the public eye.

48:33.995 --> 48:35.826
There is a momentum for us,

48:37.624 --> 48:41.742
a sense ofjoy and celebration,
which you would be wise to acknowledge.

48:41.836 --> 48:45.670
The people can Clearly see the sincerity
of the love between Margaret and me,

48:45.757 --> 48:49.545
and I would advise you
not to reprehend us for that.

48:49.636 --> 48:51.422
Such an act could backfire.

48:52.430 --> 48:57.265
And now,
if I may give you some advice in turn, Peter.

48:58.520 --> 49:00.932
That when referring to a member
of the Royal Family,

49:01.022 --> 49:05.356
you use the appropriate title.
In this case, "Her Royal Highness."

49:05.610 --> 49:08.226
When referring to the woman I love,
and who loves me,

49:08.363 --> 49:12.276
and who is soon to be my wife,
I'll call her what I damn well like.

49:12.492 --> 49:14.028
Her name is Margaret.

49:17.997 --> 49:19.578
Car, Townsend.

49:20.792 --> 49:23.033
Waiting.

49:24.003 --> 49:27.962
TiCk, tick, tiCk.

49:35.557 --> 49:37.889
Bon voyage.

49:42.856 --> 49:44.721
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

49:46.526 --> 49:49.017
MARGARET: A tiny white community,

49:49.279 --> 49:52.988
surrounded by primitive Africans,

